Correction: 107+40 are submarines, of which 40 are also rollercoasters, so the chance of being a rollercoaster given that a book is a submarine is instead 40/(107+40): 27%. Adjusting downwards, this is 22%.

I downloaded a kaggle dataset of past NYT bestsellers (https://www.kaggle.com/dhruvildave/new-york-times-best-sellers), and calculated the chance on a book being a "submarine": going down and then back up again, and a "rollercoaster": going down, then back up again, then down, then back up again.

Unless I'm mistaken, "More than 18" now impossible, so the only options left are "Between 9 and 13" and "Between 14 and 18". We're sitting at 13 weeks on the best seller list with 4 chances left. According to my modeling, Think Again is on a downward trajectory, but has a standard deviation of about 6 ranking spots. This means, to appear on the list next week, it would have to be about 1 standard deviation above my model's expectation. I estimate this to be about a 15% chance. If this does not happen it then has three remaining chances each with diminishing probability. When I calculated it out, it came to about a 68%, but I made a lot of assumptions that could be wrong, so I'll bias toward the crowd. Chart: https://github.com/jonathanmann/gjopen/blob/master/think_again_rank/ThinkAgainRegPlot.png Data: https://github.com/jonathanmann/gjopen/blob/master/think_again_rank/ThinkAgainWeeks.csv Code: https://github.com/jonathanmann/gjopen/blob/master/think_again_rank/BestSellerWeeks.py

It did dip off the list this week, but among books that lasted between 9-18 total weeks on the list (in my data since August of last year), 9 out of 10 dropped off at some point before coming back and getting more weeks. In my limited data set, four books lasted a total of 9-18 weeks dropped off later into their run, and after coming back accrued an additional 1, 3, 4, and 4 weeks. Others dipped off earlier, but that's likely similar to how Think Again sharply dipped to rank 10 early on. Think Again has been on for 9 weeks, so any of those 1-4 options would put it in the 9-13 bucket. However, if it comes back for 4, then all it would take is for it to reappear at rank 15 for a single week to put it over, a phenomenon which itself isn't uncommon.

I've finally been able to put together some data on this with the past 7 months of best seller data, since the NYT dev thing is difficult to use. First point is that it's pretty rare for a book to be on the list for 14-18 weeks. Since August 23, 22 books have been on the list at least once whose total number of weeks is >8 (and aren't on the current list). 8 have totaled 9-13 weeks, 12 have totaled 18+ weeks, but only two hit 14-18. Both of the books that hit 14-18 were from entries at rank 13-15, one for 1 week at rank 14 and one for 3 weeks at 15-13-15. The 9-13 books simply fell off the list at an average of rank 12. It seems like hitting the 14-18 bucket is mostly whether you luck into a couple extra lowest-rank weeks, which most books didn't do. The downward trajectory of Think Again is a bit too steep to justify a strong 18+ prediction, so a decent outside rate, admittedly based off of only 10 books, would be 80% 9-13 and 20% 14-18.

Looking at the distribution of # of weeks on list for the most recent 3 lists (Feb 21, Feb 28, March 7), it is heavily skewed towards lower numbers. About 1/3 of the books on the list each week are brand new, with only about 1/2 of them making it to a second week. The churn rate is pretty high. About 1/3 of books on the list have been on there for upwards of 14 weeks (and still counting!), but they would represent a small fraction of the number of new books that have come and gone (~4-5 books per week?), definitely below 10% overall but higher when you take into account only the population of books that have made it at least 3 weeks.
